This report covers the longitudinal models of the MIECHV effectiveness and of statewide trends. It is relevant to Aim 1C (“Evaluate the frequency of referrals coming into EBHV agencies”), Aim 3A (“Continually evaluate the flow of clients served per county”), Aim 3D (“Evaluate effectiveness of new engagement enhancement strategies”), and Aim 5C (“Implement and evaluate system of quality improvements and controls”) of HRSA/ACF D89MC23154 Investigation.

The underlying dataset contains information from 20 lead nurse regions, 31,043 completed referrals, 11,343 completed enrollments, and 240,325 completed visits. It summarizes C1 referrals between 2009-01-15 and 2015-10-15. Time and effort data is available from 2012-06-15 to 2015-08-14. The date used for the introduction of MIECHV funds is NA.

The processes for gathering and reshaping the C1 data was described in C1 Activity Methods.

1 Milestones

One of this investigation’s goals is to assess if C1 performance changes following significant events in Oklahoma’s home visiting programs. The following dates are of particular interest. A more detailed is found on our project’s interactive timeline.

2 Modeling and Graphical Analysis

The outcomes of interest involve the referrals, enrollments, and visits of a C1 region. The MIECHV treatment is operationalized in two ways. In Model 1, a county’s treatment effect reflects the time period when it was under contract with OSDH; the corresponding coefficients are 1a-1e. In Model 2, the treatment effect reflects county had at least one MIECHV-funded nurse on staff; the corresponding coefficients are 2a-2e. For Models 1 and 2, the “MIECHV Era” is divided into two phases (the first 19 months and the next 24). Models 3 through 7 examine specific events related to the service, and keep the MIECHV Era as a single uniform period.

A two-level Poisson link is used in each model; the outcome at each month is nested within region. The Poisson offset is the region’s number of infants in need, which helped make the regions’ estimates more comparable. Level 1 estimates an intercept and a lag-3 autocorrelation for each region. Level 2 contains two classes of variables: the first attempts to partial out variability unrelated to MIECHV events, while the second addresses the investigation’s hypotheses. The first class estimates the overall level for each quarter year (to remove seasonal and secular trends) and a lag-3 autocorrelation (to control for longitudinal dependencies). The second class estimates a coefficient for the following five comparisons.

  • Coefficient a: Initial differences between MIECHV and comparison regions.
  • Coefficient b: State-wide differences during the first 15 months of MIECHV activity (compared to before any region had MIECHV).
  • Coefficient c: State-wide differences during the next 24 months of MIECHV activity (compared to before any region had MIECHV).
  • Coefficient d: Differences between MIECHV and comparison regions during the first 15 months.
  • Coefficient e: Differences between MIECHV and comparison regions during the next 24 months.

The coefficients for d and e are the most relevant to the investigation. Significant positive values would indicate that the 6 MIECHV regions are increasing more than the 14 comparison regions (or alternatively, that they are decreasing less). The change column is the most easy to interpret; it represents the proportion difference attributed to each effect, beyond the influence of the model’s other terms. For example, a value of 1.26 for e indicates that the Phase 2 contributed to a 26% increase for the MIECHV regions. Furthermore a value of 0.73 for a in referrals indicates that the MIECHV regions started with 27% fewer referrals. The main text contains only the salient coefficients listed above; comprehensive model output is available in the appendix and online.

MIECHV Contracted

  • Model 1: MIECHV Contracted: This indicator variable reflects the months each region had at least one MIECHV county under contract. The two formula grant counties (ie, Kay and Garfield) started in May 2011, while the four competition grant counties (ie, Comanche, Muskogee, Oklahoma, and Tulsa) started in October 2011. Coefficients a-e are reported for Model 1.

MIECHV Staffed

  • Model 2: MIECHV Nurses Staffed: Some counties hired MIECHV-funded nurses in April 2012, while some could not fill it reliably until the summer of 2014. The model uses the MiechvStaffed variable, which is 1 during any month the region has at least one MIECHV-funded nurse, and 0 otherwise. Coefficients a-e are reported for Model 2.

Isolated Events

Additionally, a model was run for each of the five events to estimate it’s correspondence with each outcome. The change associated with the event is the only coefficient listed in the main text. Although the other coefficients in the event models differ from each other and the two-phase model, they are similar enough to exclude in the main text. Comprehensive model output is available in the appendix and online. A model was run for each of the following events:

  • Model 3: ParentPRO Community Connector in a county. The two urban regions started in May 2012, while the remaining four regions started 2 years later in the fall of 2014. The model accommodates the start date of each region.
  • Model 4: First marketing wave. The model accounts for the seven months of ParentPRO advertisements in 2014 for the six MIECHV regions. Although residents in non-MIECHV areas were exposed to some of the campaign (particularly through the day-time television commercials) the model ignores this affect because it’s impractical to assess how much exposure there was. Consequently, this reported result may be an underestimate of the campaign’s true effect.
  • Model 5: Internal PHI sharing. The requirement was relaxed in May 2014 for the six MIECHV regions in order to make referrals more time efficient.
  • Model 6: ParentPRO website. A client-focused website was deployed in April 2015. This is the only event in the list that applies to the entire state. The models for the other events employ non-MIECHV regions as a comparison condition.
  • Model 7: Second marketing wave. This period during 2015 is handled similarly to the first marketing wave.

A Poisson link was chosen because it typically models counts well. For additional assurance, a conventional model with a Guassian link was run on a equivalent outcome. For instance, when the Poisson outcome and offset were ‘Referral Count’ and ‘Infant Need Count’ the accompanying Guassian outcome was simply ‘Referral Count per Infants in Need’. The two approaches lead to comparable conclusions.

A longitudinal graph accompanies each outcome. A colored line follows the monthly trajectory of a single region. The six MIECHV regions are a thick colored line, while the fourteen comparison regions are thin. The region’s ID precedes its initial value and follows its final value. The two groups of regions are each summarized by a dark gray loess curve; the MIECHV group is a thick black line, while the comparison group is a thin black line. A faint gray band marks the standard error of each loess curve. Notable dates in MIECHV’s development are marked by faint vertical lines; the start of the two MIECHV phases are coral, while the six events are tan.

3 Referrals

The first model assessed how the MIECHV program affects the number of suitable referrals. The first section addresses the two-phase model; the three years before MIECHV is compared to the Phase 1 (ie, the first 19 months) and Phase 2 (ie, the next 24 months) of the service. The second section examines the correspondence between an event and an outcome. The six events are analyzed in separate models.

Two-phase Era

As seen in 1a, the MIECHV regions started with fewer referrals (per infants in need); in Figure zzz, notice how the thick black summary line is beneath the thinner gray line. This deficit doesn’t necessary indicate that these regions’ personnel are underperforming. An equally likely explanation is that the regions’ environments had client populations more difficult to reach; recall the MIECHV regions are partially composed of the state’s two large urban areas (encompassing Tulsa and Oklahoma City).

Coefficients 1b and 1c are significantly and progressively under 1.00, indicating a comparison regions’ trend of fewer and fewer suitable referrals occurring. However coefficients 1d and 1e are significantly over 1.00, indicating that the six MIECHV regions are outperforming the fourteen comparison regions. Furthermore, 1b + 1d net a number over 1.00 (and c + e do too), indicating MIECHV regions observed a small improvement in overall referrals. This pattern is evident in Figure zzz; notice how the thin gray line declines during the seven year period, while the thick black line slightly rises.

Model 2’s estimates corresponded very closely to Model 1, suggesting that the two operationalizations of the MIECHV treatment are comparable for suitable referrals.

Individual Events

Model 3 associates the presence of a Community Connector (the urban counties began in May 2012, while the other were October 2014) with a 10% increase in suitable referrals. However Model 4 associated the first advertising wave (beginning in April 2014) with a 17% drop; as stated above, the marketing influence likely bled outside the MIECHV regions, producing an underestimate. This suspicion is partially supported by Model 5, which suggests that the onset of internal sharing of PHI (in May 2014, just one month after the first ads appeared) corresponded with a 6% increase. Collinearity is not a concern because these predictors exist in separate models. Models 6 and 7 have large p-values, showing no evidence of an effect for the deployment of the state website (April 2015) or the second advertising wave (Summer 2015).

4 Enrollments

The next batch of models assessed MIECHV’s effect on completed enrollments, which occurs after the client’s first completed visit. As seen in 1a, the MIECHV regions started with 36% fewer enrollments (per infants in need); in Figure zzz, notice how the thick black summary line is beneath the thinner gray line.

Two-phase Era

Coefficients 1b and 1c are significantly less than 1.00, indicating the comparison regions’ trend of fewer completed enrollments. Coefficients 1d and 1e are greater than 1.00, but only 1e is significiant; this indicate that the six MIECHV regions are outperforming the fourteen comparison regions during MIECHV’s second phase. However, b + d net a value under 1.00 (and c + e do too), indicating MIECHV regions observed a decline in overall enrollments (but a much less steep decline than comparisons). This pattern is evident in Figure zzz; notice how the thin gray line descends sharply during the seven year period, while the thick black line declines more gradually. The groups’ enrollment rates are almost equal by December 2015.

Model 2’s estimates corresponded very closely to Model 1, suggesting that the two operationalizations of the MIECHV treatment are comparable for completed enrollments.

Individual Events

Model 4 associated the first advertising wave (beginning in April 2014) with a 36% drop. Similarly Model 5, suggests that the onset of internal sharing of PHI (in May 2014) corresponded with a 26% drop. Models 6 and 7 have large p-values, showing no evidence of an effect for the deployment of the state website (April 2015) or the second advertising wave (Summer 2015).

5 Completed Visits Per Need

The first visit outcome is visits per need, which closely resembles the previous model of enrollment per need, as seen in Figure zzz and Table zzz. The MIECHV regions started with lower values, but this gap narrowed as both groups declined during the seven years. The gap closed more quickly in the last 24 months than the first 19.

Two-phase Era

Coefficients 1b and 1c are significantly less than 1.00, indicating the comparison regions’ trend of 6% fewer suitable visits being completed. Coefficients 1d and 1e are significantly greater than 1.00, indicating that the six MIECHV regions are outperforming the fourteen comparison regions during MIECHV’s second phase. However, b + d net a value under 1.00 (and c + e do too), indicating MIECHV regions observed a decline in overall enrollments (but a less steep decline than comparisons).

Model 2’s estimates corresponded very closely to Model 1, suggesting that the two operationalizations of the MIECHV treatment are comparable for completed visits

6 Completed Visits Per Enrollment

The second visit outcome is visits per enrollment, which exhibited a different pattern than the previous three outcomes. Visits per enrollment can be interpreted as a type of efficiency: after a client has been enrolled, is the nurse able to sustain the number of visits?

Two-phase Era

The MIECHV regions started with approximately the same rate of visits (per enrollment); the p-value for 1a is large. The non-MIECHV regions experienced a 13% improvement in Phase 1, compared to before (see 1b in Table zzz). However recall from the two previous sections that these regions simultaneously experienced a 28% decline in enrollments and a 15% decline in visits (from mid-2012 to Dec 2013), so this improved efficiency is not an unqualified success. The MIECHV regions during Phase 1 were 6% worse than the non-MIECHV regions; the sum of 1b and 1d show they still experienced a 7% improvement in Phase 1, compare to before. However recall that their enrollments and visits also declined during Phase 1, but not as much as the non-MIECHV regions.

Coefficients 1c and 1e are close to 1.00 and nonsignificant, which suggests there was no difference (c) between Phase 2 and the pre-MIECHV phase or (e) between the MIECHV and comparison regions during Phase 2. Model 2’s estimates corresponded very closely to Model 1, suggesting that the two operationalizations of the MIECHV treatment are comparable for suitable referrals.

In the visits per enrollment graph (Figure zzz), the loess smoothers do not seem to correspond well with the models. We believe the discrepancy is because the the loess is using the equivalent of a Gaussian link, while the models are using a Poisson link. This discrepancy wasn’t large with the three previous outcomes (that all used “per Infants in Need” as the ratio’s denominator), but the “per Enrollments” denominator here is much more variable. Notice the large spikes that are not captured by the black lines. The corresponding ratio has a very large right skew (meaning that there are infrequent, but extreme values much larger than the mean and median), and the loess cannot accommodate the non-Gaussian region trajectories. In contrast, the Poisson link used by the models is well suited for this type of rate outcome. Also, notice each region’s large month-to-month variability for visits per enrollment, which results in much smaller lag coefficients than for visits per need.

The number of referrals, enrollments, and visits (per need) increased for MIECHV counties. The declines demonstrated in 1d possibly suggest it was difficult for MIECHV regions to sustain their visit efficiency initially, in response to the increase number of clients receiving serviced. However the gap closed during Phase 2, proposes the MIECHV regions adapted adequately. (This proposal is supported by adding coefficients 1c and 1e in the subsequent outcome, visits per nurse day. The sum exceeds 1.00, indicating the count of visits per nurse day increases for MIECHV regions during Phase 2.)

The same caveats for Models 1 and 2 with this outcome apply to Models 3-7. Model 3 indicates a associates the presence of a Community Connector (the urban counties began in May 2012, while the other were October 2014) with a 10% decrease in visits per enrollment. However Model 4 associated the first advertising wave (beginning in April 2014) with an 8% increase. Model 6 indicates an 11% increase since the deployment of the state’s website (in April 2015). Models 5 and 7 provide no evidence of a correspondence between the outcome and either PHI sharing (May 2014) or the second advertising campaign (Summer 2015). The correspondence with the outcome is more likely driven by how the events affect the count of completed enrollments (ie, the ratio’s denominator), as opposed to the count of completed visits (ie, the ratio’s numerator).

7 Completed Visits Per Nurse Day

The final visit outcome is visits per nurse day, which can be interpreted as a second perspective on efficiency: for each day a nurse is working, how many visits are being completed? The outcome’s denominator (ie, the region’s count of working days per months) is much more stable than its monthly enrollment count, so the graph’s region trajectories are much calmer compared to visits per enrollment; notice the lag 1 coefficient is 6.5 times stronger. As a result, the loess summaries in the graph once again closely agree to the Poisson models.

This outcome is examined during a shorter timeframe than the previous outcomes. June 2012 is the starting point (insted of January 2009) because the OSDH switched to a new “Time & Effort” database system, and the values from before were not directly comparable. The switch occurred roughly at the beginning of Phase 1, so the only time comparison is Phase 1 vs Phase 2; therefore coefficients 1b and 1d are not estimated.

Two-phase Era

The MIECHV and non-MIECHV regions had comparable levels during Phase 1 (note 1a is close to 1.00 with a nonsignificant p-value). Similarly, 1c indicates the two phases had similar levels during Phase 1 and Phase 2. However the MIECHV regions had a significantly 4% better productivity than and comparison regions. This is reflected by the gap between the two black loess lines that emerges soon before Phase 2 begins.

It is interesting that the model could detect the significance of a 4% difference with this outcome, when larger differences were not detected for some previous outcomes. This is likely to due to the cleaner visits per nurse day signal. When enrollment is in the numerator or denominator of an outcome, the trajectories are much noisier, which weakens power. This hints that visits per nurse day is a good candidate for future interventions, including the C1 best practice workshops.

Again Model 2’s estimates corresponded very closely to Model 1, but its coefficients are closer to 1.00. We believe this is because the “staffing” component of Model 2 is partially absorbed by the outcome’s denominator (ie, count of working days).

Individual Events

Models 4 and 5 indicate small yet significant correspondence between the first marketing campaign and PHI sharing with the outcome. As previously stated, small 3% and 4% differences were better detected with this outcome than noisier ones. The events in the remaining three models were not significant. The internal PHI sharing was not intended primarily to affect visit efficiency, but it’s reasonable to assume that a more streamlined referral and enrollment process provided the nurses with more time to dedicate to visits and servicing clients.
